SEC. 5.

Qualifications of the Chairperson and the Members of the Professional Regulatory Board of Psychology.

â The Chairperson and members of the Board shall, at the time of their appointment and for the course of their term, possess the following qualifications:

A natural born citizen and resident of the Philippines;

At least thirty-five (35) years of age;

Possess good moral character;

Hold a doctorate degree in psychology conferred by a university, college or school in the Philippines or abroad duly recognized and/or accredited by the Commission on Higher Education (CHED);

Have at least ten (10) years of practice in psychology and psychometrics in a duly recognized institution, clinic or center, as well as at least five (5) years of teaching experience in the field of psychology;

Be a registered and licensed psychologist, except in the case of the first member of the Board who shall automatically be conferred a valid certificate of registration and a valid professional identification card in psychology and psychometrics upon appointment to the Board;

Is neither an officer, trustee nor member of the faculty of any university, college, institute or school where a regular course in psychology is offered or taught or review classes conducted and shall not have any pecuniary interest, direct or indirect, in any such institution;

Is not an officer, nor hold any position other than being a member of the integrated and accredited national organization of psychologists; and

Shall not have been convicted of any crime involving moral turpitude.

SEC. 7.

Powers and Duties.

â The Board shall have the following powers and duties:

Administer and implement the provision of this Act and promulgate as well as revise or update, as necessary, rules and regulations, resolutions and guidelines hereto:

Provided,

That the policies, resolutions, rules and regulations issued or promulgated by the Board shall be subject to review and approval of the Commission;

Supervise and monitor the registration, licensure and practice of psychologists and psychometrics in the Philippines;

Administer oaths in connection with the administration of this Act;

Issue, and upon compliance with due process requirements, suspend or revoke and/or reinstate, the certificate of registration and professional identification card for psychologists and psychometricians;

Adopt an official seal of the Board;

Monitor the conditions and circumstances affecting the practice of psychology and psychometrics in the Philippines and adopt such measures as may be deemed lawful and proper for the enhancement and maintenance of high professional, ethical and technical standards of the profession;

Issue permits to and exercise visitorial powers over agencies, institutions, associations, corporations and partnerships to verify that the persons practicing psychology and psychometricians with valid certificates of registration and valid professional identification cards, and that they possess the necessary accreditation, skills and/or facilities to competently carry out their functions;

Assist the Commission in the formulation and implementation of the guidelines on continuing professional education for psychologist and psychometricians;

Ensure, in coordination with the CHED, that all educational institutions offering the course/program of psychology strictly comply with the policies, standards and requirements prescribed by the CHED for such course/program, especially in the areas of administration, curriculum, faculty, library and facilities;

Prepare, adopt, issue and amend, in consultation with the CHED, syllabi for the licensure examinations subjects;

SEC. 12.

Qualifications of Applicants for the Licensure Examinations for Psychologists.

â Any person may apply to take the examination for registration and licensure as a psychologist after furnishing evidence satisfactory to the Board that the applicant:

Is a Filipino citizen, a permanent resident or a citizen of a foreign state/country which extends reciprocity to the Philippines relative to the practice of the profession;

Holds at least a master's degree in psychology conferred by a university, college or school in the Philippines or abroad recognized/accredited by the CHED and has obtained sufficient credits for the subjects covered in the examination;

Has undergone a minimum of two hundred (200) hours of supervised practicum/internship/clinical experience related to services enumerated in paragraph (b) of Section 3 of this Act and under the auspices of a licensed psychologist or other licensed mental health professional;

Is of good moral character; and

Has not been convicted of an offense involving moral turpitude.

SEC. 26.

Suspension or Revocation of Certificate of Registration and Professional Identification Card or Cancellation of a Special/Temporary Permit.

â The Board shall have the power, after notice and hearing, to suspend or revoke the certificate of registration and professional identification card or to cancel special/temporary permits granted pursuant to this Act on any ground set forth in Section 33 of this Act or any of the instances hereunder:

Procurement of a certificate of registration and/or professional identification card or special/temporary permit by fraud or deceit;

Allowing an unqualified person to advertise or to practice the profession by using one's certificate of registration or professional identification card or special/temporary permit;

Violating or conspiring to violate any of the provisions of this Act, its implementing rules and regulations, the code of ethics or code of professional standards promulgated hereinafter by the Board;

Manifest physical or mental incompetence to render psychological services with reasonable skill and safety to his/her clients/patients;

Manifest physical or mental incompetence to render psychological services with reasonable skill and safety to his/her clients/patients;

Professional misconduct or negligence in the performance of duties as a psychologist or psychometrician; and

Engaging in the practice of the profession during the period of one's suspension.

SEC. 33.

Prohibited Acts.

â

No person shall:

Engage in the professional practice of psychology or psychometrics nor represent himself/herself as a professional practicing psychologist or psychometrician without a valid certificate of registration or valid professional identification card, or a valid special/temporary permit granted by the Board pursuant to this Act;

Represent himself/herself to be a licensed and authorized practicing psychologist or psychometrician during the time that his/her certificate of registration has been suspended or revoked or professional identification card without being renewed, or special/temporary permit cancelled;

Allow any other person to use his/her certificate of registration and professional identification card or special/temporary permit for any purpose, regardless of whether such act actually enables the unqualified individual to engage in the practice of psychology or psychometrics;

